Narrative Games: Part 2
Seth Bloomberg
Kunal Goel
Red Sheehan

an hour ago   14 min read

This report was originally published as an Enterprise tier report on June 11, 2024.

Key Insights

  • Messari Research holds quarterly "Narrative Games" meetings to assess the potential of compelling narratives based on token supply overhang, impact, probability, and market consensus.
  • This second part of Narrative Games covers the AI x Crypto intersection, SocialFi, and Bitcoin Programmability.
  • The AI x Crypto intersection specifically focuses on inference networks. New protocol launches and excitement around TGEs will likely overcome the downside of supply overhang, but as is the case with all infrastructure layers, inference networks will need to find real demand drivers.
  • Decentralized SocialFi is the financialization layer for decentralized social. It promises to accelerate the adoption of decentralized social through new and powerful financial incentives for creator and user growth.
  • Bitcoin has largely been viewed as a store of value, while other alternative L1s have become more akin to tech platforms for application development. Now, this is changing, as Bitcoin is leaning into modular programmability.

At Messari Research, we have a quarterly meeting called "Narrative Games," where we discuss which narratives are most compelling for the next 3-6 months. We identify characteristics that influence a narrative's potential for hype, financial gain, and technology adoption, and use these to create a framework for comparing different narratives based on the following criteria:

Supply Overhang

Supply overhang affects the supply-demand balance of a token, influencing price movements and investor sentiment. A large supply overhang, where many tokens are held by a few entities or scheduled for release, can create downward pressure on prices due to anticipated sell-offs. This can reduce investor enthusiasm and confidence, making even strong narratives lose momentum if the market fears an impending increase in token supply.

Impact

Impact highlights a narrative's real-world relevance and transformative potential. A narrative with significant impact means the project can solve real problems, drive adoption, or offer substantial benefits over existing solutions. This relevance boosts investor confidence, attracts developers and users, and promotes long-term growth. Impactful narratives also help distinguish a project from competitors, positioning it as a leader in innovation and value creation.

Probability

Probability in crypto narratives has two key forms for stakeholders to evaluate. First, market participants should assess the likelihood of a protocol or sector delivering on its promises. If a team cannot turn its story into reality, the narrative is useless. Identifying outcome probabilities also helps pinpoint key obstacles. Removing these obstacles, through technological or regulatory changes, can revive old narratives and spark new ones.

Second, probability analysis can gauge the likelihood of other market participants buying into a narrative. Even if a narrative identifies a technological shift, it doesnt guarantee market attention. This is like a tree falling in a forest with no one to hear itdid it happen? Similarly, if a narrative becomes reality but the market doesnt care, is it truly a narrative?

Consensus

Knowing if there is consensus about a narrative is important because it shows the collective confidence within the market, which can influence the narrative's strength and impact. Consensus indicates broad support and acceptance, suggesting the narrative has been validated by various stakeholders. This agreement can drive momentum, attract resources, and foster a robust ecosystem. Additionally, consensus reduces uncertainty and risk, as many participants share a common vision and are likely to work together.

However, a consensus narrative can also limit upside potential. When a narrative is widely accepted, much of the growth may already be priced in, reducing the opportunity for substantial gains. The best trades are often those with strong conviction but without market consensus. These trades meet all other criteria, such as impact, probability, and resource allocation, but have not yet been widely recognized, offering significant upside potential as the narrative gains traction.

This is Part 2 of the two-part report. Part 2 focuses on the AI x Crypto sector, SocialFi, and Bitcoin Programmability. Part 1 focused on DeFi and yield-related narratives; the report can be found here.

AI x Crypto Intersection Model Layer

At a high level, the AI x Crypto intersection can be divided into three layers: the base infrastructure, the model layer, and the application layer.

The base infrastructure layer is generally synonymous with compute providers. Projects such as Akash, Render, and numerous others fit into this category. More broadly, the compute leveraged at this layer can be used for both inferencing and training AI models. The model layer compromises projects such as Allora, Bittensor, and Ritual. Models can be hosted and inferenced on these networks, and they may use the base layer compute providers (e.g., Akash) to power these models. AI applications, such as MyShell, Virtuals, and Colony, package the lower-level layers into a cohesive consumer product.

Framework Evaluation

Holistically, the AI x Crypto sector is relatively nascent. From the tech stack perspective, the base layer is the most established, with many of the projects having already launched a token. Although this layer still has new projects and token generation events (TGE) ahead (e.g., IO net), on the near horizon (i.e., 3 - 6 months), the model layer will likely see more activity along each of these fronts. The focus of the evaluation here will then be on this layer in particular.

The lack of existing TGEs at the model layer generally implies that this category in particular will face large supply overhangs over the coming months and years. Assuming the majority of projects within the model layer raised traditional funding, it would be expected that they would also launch with typical float levels of around 10-20%. The Spectral network token ($SPEC), for example, is one of the only liquid tokens in this category and currently has an ~11% float level.

The extent to which applications can effectively use the model layer will ultimately determine its impact. The demos from the Wayfinder team indicate users will soon have a new form of interaction with onchain applications. But, in the short term, the model layer will likely serve more as automation tooling for DeFi applications.

A sector as universally hyped as AI x Crypto will inevitably fall short of meeting all expectations. In addition, the model layer is structurally more of an infrastructure, meaning it will take time for applications to integrate with these projects and give some indication of their potential. However, a single consumer experience or use case (e.g., ChatGPT) can catalyze an entire market. The model layer will then benefit from an expanding application layer, effectively creating more shots on goal.

Tailwinds

The broader AI x Crypto sector is a net new category. Institutional and retail markets will naturally want exposure to it. As is the case with other sectors, new protocol launches coupled with TGEs will shift the market's attention into this particular category.

The adjacent, generative AI sector serves as a continuous catalyst for the AI x Crypto sector. Historically, GPU networks have primarily benefitted from AI developments, but over the next few months, a new class (i.e., the model layer) of AI x Crypto protocols will be available to the market.

SocialFi protocols, such as Farcaster or Friend Tech, may look to integrate with one of the model layer projects to enable generative AI capabilities within their products. Depending on the architecture and integration strategy, this could kick off a wave of AI experimentation from both end-users and developers.

Headwinds

At the end of the day, the model layer represents a new set of infrastructure and tooling for applications to leverage. The broader sentiment within crypto still points to the desire to see application adoption rather than more infrastructure investment. If model layer protocols launch with multi-billion dollar FDVs with no clear structural demand, then the retail fatigue of low float / high FDV protocols may hold back this sector.

Decentralized SocialFi

Decentralized Social (DeSoc) has always been one of cryptos most promising use cases. However, despite some recent growth, the vision is far from realized. Decentralized SocialFi is the speculative and financialization layer for the nascent DeSoc sector. It hopes to accelerate DeSoc adoption by creating financial incentives for both creators and followers.

SocialFi creates a modified incentive structure from traditional social media monetization. It brings speculation into the mix, helping increase creator earnings across audience sizes. This creates a powerful incentive flywheelmore creators are incentivized to onboard and bring their audiences, which increases speculative value and generates more revenue.

Framework Evaluation

Decentralized Social promises to create a platform for the people, of the people, and by the people. Its financialization layer follows a similar ethos and aims to have a wide and distributed holder basethe recent launches of Degen and Friend.Tech have already set a precedent of high allocation to the creators and users on their respective platforms. As such, SocialFi has the lowest overhang of future supply among all our narratives.

SocialFi may realize one of many futures. It may be the future of all investing and online social interaction, but it has a low probability of success. Or, at a higher probability level, SocialFi may have a much smaller impact of simply accelerating the growth of the DeSoc sector through financial incentives. Most likely, itll be somewhere in the middle and as such we give it a middling score for impact and probability.

Finally, DeSoc is a deep consensus theme. Recently, with ~50,000 daily active users, Farcaster raised at a valuation of $1 billion from prominent crypto funds such Paradigm and a16z. SocialFi on the other hand is less consensus. While Degen trades at a valuation of $600 million, Friend.Tech is valued much cheaper at $80 million.

Tailwinds

The most important tailwind for SocialFi is the powerful incentive flywheel. While creators area always incentivized to share their content, SocialFi creates the buyer-follower who is almost as financially incentivized to share with their network, bringing more attention and value back to the creator.

SocialFi allows early-stage creators to be tokenized, so the monetizable creator pool is much, much larger. Effectively, SocialFi can start earning revenue on creators before the creators have had the time to attract paying customers, a significant advantage given the distribution of creators who actually can earn from their subscribers. Additionally, followers can be incentivized to join the platform through both value appreciation and token incentives.

Headwinds

Value generation through speculation comes at a cost. Once the speculative cycle turns, the incentive flywheel completely breaks. This phenomenon has already been seen in Friend.Tech V1 and Friend.Tech V2 seems to be losing hype quickly as well. Additionally, allowing followers to invest in creators changes the dynamics of the relationship with the creator having a responsibility to try to deliver value to the follower-buyer. A tip or donation from followers does not create these issues.

Additionally, any financialization and speculation attracts mercenaries and attackers looking to extract maximum value. This phenomenon was also seen during Friend.Tech V1 where users would create multiple accounts to buy their own keys to maximize their points without risking their capital or needing to create engaging content for their followers.

Bitcoin Programmability

Bitcoin is the oldest and most secure crypto network, with the largest cryptocurrency by market cap: BTC. However, Bitcoin has limited programmability. For this reason, it has deferred most narratives and sectors to alt-L1s throughout its history, except for BTC being a store of value and (arguably) peer-to-peer payments. However, this is changing as Bitcoin is in a renaissance of programmability and modularity.

Ordinal Theory emphasized the demand for added functionality, and then BitVM made expressive and trust-minimized L2s seem possible. The Bitcoin community is now seriously exploring soft forks for additional opcodes and even overall script overhauls.

Framework Evaluation

Ethereums aggregate L2 FDV is roughly $50 billion. BTCs market cap is 3x that of ETH, so to be conservative (as this sector is not as established), well assume Bitcoin layers could be 1.5x the size of Ethereum L2s. This gives an estimated FDV of $75 billion. Currently the circulating market cap of Bitcoin layers is $8 billion, 10.6% of the estimated FDV. Most layers are in development and/or dont yet have tokens launched.

BTC is home to nearly half of the liquidity of the entire cryptocurrency sector and is where most users get started. The opportunity to unlock a trillion dollars in liquidity is massive. Bitcoin is the longest-running network with the most trust in its security. Applications launched on this network could easily be seen as more legitimate than those on any other crypto network.

A soft fork is required to enable unilateral exits from rollups through covenants. Soft fork network upgrades are notoriously difficult to coordinate on Bitcoin. However, there is broad support for one in particular: op_cat. And even if there is no soft fork, the extent of BitVMs capabilities has barely been explored. Limitations breed creativity, and were still learning the limitations of Bitcoin Script after so many years.

The desire for Bitcoin programmability became undeniable after Ordinals took off. However, achieving expressive programmability through BitVM, and especially on rollups enabled by a soft fork activation, is looked at with skepticism.

Tailwinds

More Users

Think of your favorite crypto sector/narrative: NFTs, DeFi, DePIN, RWAs, memecoins, DeSoc, onchain governance, etc. If it could have been built on Bitcoin the first time around, it would have. Its only on your [favorite alt-L1 here] because it couldnt be built on Bitcoin. However, this is changing. And that means the greater Bitcoin ecosystem will eat your lunch as all of cryptos narratives will be able to live on Bitcoin, on modular layers. The network effect, mindshare, and user base of Bitcoin run through all other ecosystems due to being first.

More Liquidity

NFTs were an early case study on the power of Bitcoins liquidity. Ethereum essentially had a decade-long head start on NFTs, and in roughly a year since Ordinals were created, 4 of the top 20 collections by market cap are on Bitcoin. At one point in 2024, 3 of the top 5 were Bitcoin collections.

In the past six months, Bitcoin has seen $2.75 billion in NFT sales volume. For reference, Ethereum and Solana have seen $2.78 billion in sales volume in the same period, combined. Inscriptions have accounted for 17.5% of total transaction fees in the past 6 months ($170 million of $973 million total). BTC ETFs have seen $14.8 billion in net ETF flows. ETF demand may not directly translate to onchain BTC utilization in other ecosystems, but do you really think TradFi will stop at spot? No, they want yield. And centralized yield services (cough, Celsius and co.) have proven suboptimal.

Headwinds

Technological Limitations

The main challenge for Bitcoin L2s is that rollups, the most desired type of L2s, are simply not possible on Bitcoin today. A real Bitcoin rollup would enable unilateral exits from Bitcoin L1, host data availability in Bitcoin blocks, and enforce the validity of rollup state transitions on Bitcoin L1; none of these aspects are solved today.

Unilateral exits from a rollup are impossible without covenants, which require a soft fork for an opcode like cat or ctv. Bitcoin has 576 MB/day of DA; For reference, Ethereum (4844), Celestia, and EigenDA offer DA rates of 7 thousand, 576 thousand, 1.3 million MB/day, respectively. BitVM models have proven that onchain verification of offchain computation is indeed possible. However, it has scaling limitations and liquidity requirements that have not been extensively tested in production.

Actual Demand

Lets say the tech limitations are solved. Great, now Bitcoin L2s win, right? Maybe not. There are two camps of Bitcoin L2 enthusiasts: those who want to extend Bitcoin the network and those who want to extend BTC the asset.

The former will not settle for alt-DA validium models; its Bitcoin security (including Bitcoin DA) or nothing. And weve already seen the big blockers fail at going down the route of more DA. And for the latter, if Bitcoin L2s can build trust-minimized bridges with unilateral exits through op_cat-powered covenants, why cant Ethereum, Solana, or Abitrum do the same? Theres no moat if the only motivation is to unlock liquidity.

Closing Thoughts

Given the influence of emerging narratives on crypto markets, Messari Research hosts a quarterly Narrative Games meeting to evaluate their potential based on token supply overhang, impact, probability, and market consensus. In part two of this report, we highlight several narratives, including themes around AI x Crypto intersection, Decentralized SocialFi, and Bitcoin Programmability.

The AI x Crypto intersection, specifically the model layer, will likely see many new projects launch along with TGE over the coming months. While this will definitely pique the interest of many market participants, it will naturally create large supply overhangs. To reach its full potential, this layer will need to integrate with compelling applications. Given its high impact and probability, it maintains a score of 3.5 out of 5.

Decentralized SocialFi is the explicit speculative and financialization layer for the nascent DeSoc sector. The vision is to expand the earning potential of all creators while also presenting upside potential for those who invest early. SocialFi TGE have generally seen low-to-minimal supply overhang, but the impact and probability rank relatively lower; as such, it scores a 3.5 out of 5.

Bitcoin programmability presents the opportunity to add a new value proposition for the BTC asset. Ordinals' early impact and attention indicate the appetite for adding programmability and modularity to Bitcoin. Virtually all early protocols and initiatives have yet to release a token, implying large supply overhangs ahead. Given the size of the network and asset, the impact would be monumental, but currently, the probability ranks relatively much lower. Altogether, this narrative scores a 4 out of 5.
